================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emOwnPtrArray.h: owning array of heap-allocated pointers (non-copyable).

2 files outside emCore use this type.

Only 2 emCore consumers:
  emFontCache.h:85  — emOwnPtrArray<Entry> EntryArray
  emFpPlugin.h:349  — emOwnPtrArray<emFpPlugin> Plugins

Rust equivalent: Vec<T> (owned values) or Vec<Box<T>> (heap-allocated).

Method mapping (same functionality, different names):
  GetCount     -> Vec::len()
  Add          -> Vec::push()
  Insert       -> Vec::insert()
  Remove       -> Vec::remove()
  Clear        -> Vec::clear()
  IsEmpty      -> Vec::is_empty()
  Sort         -> Vec::sort_by()
  operator[]   -> index operator
  begin/end    -> .iter()

Composable from stdlib:
  BinaryInsert       -> binary_search_by() + insert()
  BinaryRemoveByKey  -> binary_search_by() + remove()
  VERIFIED: Outside-emCore files that call these methods:
    - emAvClient.cpp: Properties.BinarySearchByKey() with Insert() on negative index (~i pattern)
    - emTimeZonesModel.cpp: Cities.BinarySearchByKey() with Insert() on negative index (~i pattern)
  Both use binary search to find sorted position, then Insert at (~index) for new elements.
  Conclusion: Vec<T> (or Vec<Box<T>>) is sufficient. BinaryInsert/BinaryRemoveByKey are
  composable from stdlib binary_search_by() + insert()/remove(). No specialized port needed.

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  Set(index, ptr) / Reset(index) — replace element at index, delete old.
    Rust equivalent: vec[index] = new_value (Drop runs on old value).
  Release(index) — release ownership without deleting.
    Rust equivalent: std::mem::take() or vec.remove().
  Compact / capacity management — Vec handles this internally.

Open question 1 investigated: "Does emFontCache EntryArray have a Rust equivalent?"
  C++ emFontCache uses emOwnPtrArray<Entry> as a dynamic cache of font
  entries. Rust emFontCache.rs replaces the entire structure with a single
  static OnceLock<emImage> holding one decoded font atlas (emFontCache.rs:28).
  The EntryArray concept does not exist in Rust — the Rust version is a
  fixed single-atlas approach rather than a dynamic multi-entry cache.

Open question 2 investigated: "Does emFpPlugin Plugins array have a Rust equivalent?"
  C++ uses emOwnPtrArray<emFpPlugin>. Rust uses Vec<emFpPlugin>
  (emFpPlugin.rs:438). Direct mapping — the array is sorted by descending
  priority (emFpPlugin.rs:479-480).
